(46, 1, 25, 45, 11, 33, 36, 'foolishness of God is wiser than men', 'Wisdom and Knowledge of God', 'Both passages emphasize the superiority of God''s wisdom and strength over human understanding. The phrase ''foolishness of God is wiser than men'' in 1 Corinthians connects with the idea of God''s unsearchable wisdom in Romans.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 25, 38, 4, 6, 7, 'the weakness of God is stronger than men', 'Divine Strength vs. Human Weakness', 'Both passages emphasize the superiority of God''s power over human limitations. 1 Corinthians highlights God''s wisdom and strength, while Zechariah underscores that success is not achieved by human might but by God''s spirit.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 25, 46, 1, 18, 18, 'foolishness of God', 'Foolishness and Power of God', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between human perception and divine wisdom. The ''foolishness of God'' in the source verse relates to the ''preaching of the cross'' being perceived as foolishness by those who perish.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 25, 47, 13, 4, 4, 'weakness of God is stronger than men', 'Power in Weakness', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between weakness and power. 1 Corinthians highlights God''s wisdom and strength in perceived foolishness and weakness, while 2 Corinthians illustrates Christ''s crucifixion through weakness and subsequent life by God''s power.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 25, 7, 7, 2, 8, 'the weakness of God is stronger than men', 'Divine Strength in Weakness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme that God''s ways defy human expectations. In Judges, God reduces Gideon''s army to demonstrate that His strength surpasses human might, aligning with the idea that ''the weakness of God is stronger than men.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 25, 38, 12, 7, 8, 'weakness of God is stronger than men', 'Strength in Weakness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of strength arising from perceived weakness. In 1 Corinthians, the ''foolishness'' and ''weakness'' of God surpass human wisdom and strength, while Zechariah highlights that the ''feeble'' among Jerusalem will be made strong, akin to David.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 25, 46, 1, 27, 29, 'foolishness of God is wiser than men', 'Foolishness and Weakness of God', 'This connection highlights how both passages emphasize that God''s wisdom and strength are contrary to human expectations. The ''foolishness of God'' and ''weakness of God'' in the source verse are echoed in the target passage, which discusses how God chooses ''foolish things'' and ''weak things'' to confound the wise and mighty.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 59, 2, 5, 5, 'not many noble', 'Divine Choice of the Lowly', 'This connection highlights God''s preference for the ''poor'' and ''not many noble'' in His calling. Both passages emphasize that those considered lowly or unwise by worldly standards are chosen for God''s purposes.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 46, 3, 18, 20, 'not many wise men after the flesh', 'Wisdom and Foolishness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between worldly wisdom and divine wisdom. In 1 Corinthians 1:26, the calling of the ''wise men'' is questioned, while 1 Corinthians 3:18-20 warns against self-deception in worldly wisdom.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 59, 1, 9, 11, 'not many noble, are called', 'Connection of Humility and Exaltation', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between the lowly and the rich. 1 Corinthians highlights that not many wise or noble are called, while James encourages the lowly to rejoice in their exaltation, indicating a divine reversal of status.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 40, 11, 25, 26, 'not many wise men after the flesh', 'Connection of Wisdom and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize that not many wise are called or understand divine truths. They highlight the contrast between the wise and the humble, suggesting that revelation is given to those who are considered ''babes'' rather than the ''wise and prudent.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'not many wise men after the flesh', 'Calling and Ignorance of the Wise', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine calling contrasted with human wisdom. Both passages emphasize that the wise and powerful of this world fail to recognize God''s plan, leading to the crucifixion of Christ.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 42, 10, 21, 21, 'not many wise men after the flesh', 'Connection of Wisdom and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize that not many wise are called, highlighting a theme of divine revelation to the humble. In 1 Corinthians, the calling excludes the wise, while in Luke, wisdom is hidden from the wise and revealed to babes.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 26, 42, 18, 24, 25, 'not many noble, are called', 'Wealth and Calling in Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the difficulty for the ''rich'' and ''noble'' to enter the kingdom of God. This connection highlights how those considered wise or powerful by worldly standards are often not the ones called to salvation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 59, 2, 5, 5, 'God hath chosen the foolish things', 'Connection of Divine Choice', 'Both passages emphasize God''s choice of the weak and poor to fulfill His purposes. This connection highlights how God values faith and humility over worldly wisdom and strength.', 'theme', 0.6359999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 40, 11, 25, 25, NULL, 'Connection of Wisdom and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between the wise and the weak or simple. 1 Corinthians highlights how God confounds the wise, while Matthew shows that God reveals truths to the ''babes'' instead of the wise and prudent.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 46, 1, 20, 20, 'foolish things of the world', 'Wisdom and Foolishness Contrast', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between divine wisdom and worldly wisdom. The phrase ''made foolish the wisdom of this world'' in 1:20 relates to how God chooses ''the foolish things of the world'' in 1:27 to confound the wise.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 19, 8, 2, 2, 'weak things of the world', 'Strength from the Weak', 'This connection highlights how both passages emphasize the use of the weak to achieve strength and confound the mighty. In 1 Corinthians, the ''foolish things'' and ''weak things'' are chosen by God, while Psalms speaks of strength ordained from ''babes and sucklings.''', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 23, 29, 14, 14, 'the wise', 'Wisdom and Foolishness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God confounding human wisdom. In 1 Corinthians, God chooses the ''foolish things'' to challenge the wise, while Isaiah speaks of the ''wisdom of their wise men'' perishing, highlighting a similar contrast.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 42, 21, 15, 15, 'foolish things of the world', 'Wisdom and Strength in God', 'Both passages emphasize God''s provision of wisdom to the weak and foolish, showcasing how divine strength confounds human wisdom. The promise of wisdom in Luke aligns with the theme of God choosing the weak to challenge the mighty in Corinthians.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 27, 44, 4, 11, 21, 'foolish things of the world', 'Foolishness and Boldness in Faith', 'Both passages emphasize how God uses the ''foolish'' and ''weak'' to achieve His purposes. In Acts, Peter and John, perceived as ''unlearned and ignorant men,'' exemplify this divine choice, demonstrating boldness and power through their faith in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 18, 34, 24, 24, 'things which are despised', 'Divine Reversal of Power', 'Both passages emphasize God''s power to overturn the mighty and elevate the lowly. In 1 Corinthians, God chooses the despised to nullify the powerful, while Job speaks of breaking mighty men and replacing them.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 45, 4, 17, 17, 'things which are not', 'Connection of God''s Calling', 'Both passages emphasize God''s ability to call forth existence from non-existence. In 1 Corinthians, God chooses ''things which are not,'' while Romans speaks of God who ''calleth those things which be not.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 23, 2, 11, 11, 'things which are despised', 'Humility and Exaltation Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of God choosing the humble and despised to overturn the proud and lofty. Both passages emphasize the reversal of human status, where the exalted are brought low and the lowly are lifted up.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 23, 2, 17, 17, 'things which are despised', 'Humility and Divine Exaltation', 'This connection highlights the theme of God choosing the lowly and despised to overturn human pride. Both passages emphasize the humbling of the lofty and the exaltation of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 19, 37, 35, 36, 'things which are not', 'Contrast of the Wicked and Chosen', 'Both passages emphasize the transient nature of the wicked and the enduring choice of God for the despised. The ''things which are not'' in 1 Corinthians reflect the ultimate fate of the ''wicked'' who ''passed away'' in Psalms. This connection highlights the theme of God''s sovereignty over worldly power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 27, 2, 34, 35, 'things which are despised', 'Divine Choice of the Lowly', 'This connection highlights how God uses what is ''despised'' and ''things which are not'' to overturn worldly power, as seen in Daniel''s vision of a stone that destroys a mighty image. Both passages emphasize the theme of God''s sovereignty in elevating the humble to achieve His purposes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 28, 5, 28, 63, 63, 'to bring to nought', 'Divine Reversal of Fortune', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God bringing to nought. In 1 Corinthians, God chooses the despised to overturn the powerful, while in Deuteronomy, God rejoices in destroying those who have turned away. This connection highlights a divine action of reversal.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 45, 3, 27, 27, 'no flesh should glory in his presence', 'Exclusion of Boasting', 'Both passages emphasize the exclusion of boasting in God''s presence. 1 Corinthians 1:29 states that ''no flesh should glory,'' while Romans 3:27 asks, ''Where is boasting then? It is excluded.'' This connection highlights the theme of humility before God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 24, 9, 23, 23, 'glory in his presence', 'Glory and Human Limitations', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of human pride and glory. They highlight that no one should boast in their own wisdom, might, or riches, as all glory belongs to God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 49, 2, 9, 9, 'that no flesh should glory', 'Boasting in God''s Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that human efforts cannot lead to boasting before God. They highlight that salvation is not based on works, ensuring that no one can glory in His presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 45, 3, 19, 19, 'no flesh should glory in his presence', 'Glory and Guilt Before God', 'This connection highlights the theme of human accountability before God. Both passages emphasize that no one can boast in their righteousness, as all are guilty under the law.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 46, 1, 31, 31, 'glory in his presence', 'Glory in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorying in the Lord rather than in human achievements. The first verse states that ''no flesh should glory in his presence,'' while the second encourages believers to ''glory in the Lord.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 46, 4, 7, 7, 'glory in his presence', 'Glory in God''s Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that boasting or glorying is inappropriate in the presence of God. The first verse states that ''no flesh should glory in his presence,'' while the second questions why one would glory if everything is received from God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 29, 23, 10, 15, 15, 'that no flesh should glory', 'Boasting and Humility', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of boasting in one''s own strength. In 1 Corinthians, it is stated that ''no flesh should glory,'' while Isaiah uses the metaphor of tools boasting against their user, illustrating the absurdity of such pride.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 49, 1, 7, 7, 'redemption', 'Redemption and Grace Connection', 'Both passages emphasize redemption as a key theme. In 1 Corinthians, redemption is part of what Christ provides, while Ephesians highlights redemption through his blood, linking the two concepts of salvation and grace.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 50, 3, 9, 9, 'righteousness, and sanctification, and redemption', 'Connection of Righteousness in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of righteousness that comes through faith in Christ. In 1 Corinthians, righteousness is presented as a gift from God, while Philippians contrasts it with self-derived righteousness from the law.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 45, 8, 1, 1, 'in Christ Jesus', 'Connection of Being in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the state of being ''in Christ Jesus,'' which signifies a transformative relationship that leads to wisdom, righteousness, and freedom from condemnation. This connection highlights the spiritual benefits and identity of believers in Christ.', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 46, 1, 2, 2, 'sanctification', 'Connection of Sanctification in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize being sanctified in Christ Jesus. The SOURCE verse mentions sanctification as part of what Christ is made unto us, while the TARGET passage directly addresses those sanctified in Him.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 51, 1, 14, 14, 'redemption', 'Connection of Redemption in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize redemption as a key aspect of Christ''s work. In 1 Corinthians, redemption is part of what Christ provides, while Colossians specifically mentions redemption through his blood.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 46, 6, 11, 11, 'sanctification', 'Sanctification and Justification Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concepts of sanctification and justification in relation to Christ. In 1 Corinthians 1:30, believers are described as being sanctified through Christ, while 1 Corinthians 6:11 affirms that they are sanctified and justified in His name.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 30, 49, 2, 10, 10, 'in Christ Jesus', 'Connection of Creation and Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize being ''in Christ Jesus'' and highlight the transformative work of God in believers. 1 Corinthians 1:30 speaks of Christ as our wisdom and righteousness, while Ephesians 2:10 describes us as God''s workmanship created for good works.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 24, 9, 23, 24, 'let him glory in the Lord', 'Glory in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of glorifying the Lord rather than personal attributes like wisdom, might, or riches. They highlight that true understanding and knowledge of God is the basis for glory.', 'theme', 0.629, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 47, 10, 17, 17, 'let him glory in the Lord', 'Connection of Glory in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of glorifying the Lord. The identical phrase ''let him glory in the Lord'' in both verses highlights this thematic connection.', 'keyword', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 50, 3, 3, 3, 'He that glorieth, let him glory in the Lord', 'Glorying in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of rejoicing in the Lord rather than in human achievements. The call to ''glory in the Lord'' in 1 Corinthians resonates with the idea of having ''no confidence in the flesh'' in Philippians.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 19, 105, 3, 3, 'let him glory in the Lord', 'Connection of Glorifying the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the act of glorifying the Lord. 1 Corinthians 1:31 encourages believers to glory in the Lord, while Psalms 105:3 calls for rejoicing in His holy name.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 23, 41, 16, 16, 'let him glory in the Lord', 'Glory in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of rejoicing and glorying in the Lord. They highlight a common theme of finding glory and joy in God''s presence and actions.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 13, 16, 10, 10, 'let him glory in the Lord', 'Connection of Glory in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of glorifying the Lord. 1 Corinthians 1:31 encourages believers to glory in the Lord, while 1 Chronicles 16:10 calls for rejoicing in His holy name. This connection highlights a shared theme of worship and reverence.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 1, 31, 23, 45, 25, 25, 'let him glory in the Lord', 'Glory in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorifying the Lord. In 1 Corinthians, it states that those who glory should do so in the Lord, while Isaiah declares that the seed of Israel shall glory in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 46, 1, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Preaching and Wisdom', 'Both passages emphasize the avoidance of ''wisdom of words'' in preaching. This connection highlights the focus on the message of the gospel over eloquent speech, ensuring the centrality of the cross of Christ.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 46, 2, 4, 4, 'not with excellency of speech', 'Connection of Speech and Wisdom', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of Paul''s speech, contrasting human wisdom with divine demonstration. The focus is on the testimony of God rather than persuasive rhetoric.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 2, 4, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Speech and Eloquent Expression', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of eloquence in speech. Paul and Moses express their limitations in communicating effectively, highlighting their reliance on God''s message rather than their own abilities.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 45, 16, 18, 18, 'excellency of speech', 'Deception in Speech', 'This connection highlights the contrast between genuine testimony and deceptive speech. Both passages emphasize the use of words, with 1 Corinthians focusing on the simplicity of Paul''s message and Romans warning against those who use ''good words and fair speeches'' to deceive.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 55, 1, 8, 8, 'testimony of God', 'Connection of Testimony and Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the testimony of God and the call to endure afflictions for the gospel. In 1 Corinthians, Paul declares the testimony of God, while in 2 Timothy, there is an encouragement to not be ashamed of that testimony amidst suffering.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 62, 5, 11, 13, 'declaring unto you the testimony of God', 'Eternal Life and Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of declaring God''s testimony. In 1 Corinthians, Paul speaks of declaring the testimony of God, while in 1 John, the record of eternal life is presented through belief in the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 1, 24, 1, 6, 7, 'declaring unto you the testimony of God', 'Speaking Despite Inadequacy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of speaking despite personal inadequacy. Paul declares the testimony of God without relying on eloquence, while Jeremiah expresses his inability to speak due to youth, yet is commanded to deliver God''s message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 2, 48, 6, 14, 14, 'Jesus Christ, and him crucified', 'Emphasis on the Cross', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the cross in the believer''s life. They highlight a focus on Jesus Christ and his crucifixion as central to faith and identity.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 2, 43, 17, 3, 3, 'Jesus Christ', 'Knowledge of Christ and God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of knowing Jesus Christ. In 1 Corinthians, Paul focuses on Jesus Christ and his crucifixion, while John highlights knowing the true God and Jesus Christ. This connection highlights the centrality of Christ in the understanding of eternal life.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 2, 46, 1, 22, 25, 'Jesus Christ, and him crucified', 'Connection of Christ and Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Christ crucified. In 1 Corinthians 2:2, Paul focuses solely on Jesus Christ and his crucifixion, while 1 Corinthians 1:22-25 discusses the reactions to Christ crucified among Jews and Greeks.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 2, 50, 3, 8, 10, 'Jesus Christ, and him crucified', 'Knowledge of Christ''s Excellency', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on knowing Christ and his crucifixion. Both passages stress the importance of Christ''s significance over worldly values and personal righteousness.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 2, 48, 3, 1, 1, 'Jesus Christ, and him crucified', 'Connection of Crucifixion Emphasis', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus Christ and his crucifixion. This connection highlights the centrality of the crucifixion in Paul''s message to the Corinthians and the Galatians.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 3, 47, 13, 4, 4, 'in weakness', 'Connection of Weakness and Power', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of weakness leading to divine power. In 1 Corinthians, Paul speaks of his own weakness, while in 2 Corinthians, he reflects on Christ''s crucifixion through weakness and the resulting power of God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 3, 46, 4, 10, 13, 'weakness', 'Connection of Weakness and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of weakness and suffering in the life of believers. In 1 Corinthians 2:3, Paul describes his own weakness, while in 1 Corinthians 4:10-13, he contrasts this with the perceived strength and honor of others, highlighting the struggles faced by himself and fellow apostles.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 3, 47, 12, 5, 10, 'in weakness, and in fear, and in much trembling', 'Connection of Weakness and Strength', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of weakness leading to strength. In 1 Corinthians, Paul describes his presence in weakness, while in 2 Corinthians, he highlights how his weaknesses allow Christ''s power to rest upon him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 3, 44, 17, 6, 12, 'in fear, and in much trembling', 'Connection of Fear and Opposition', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of fear and trembling in the face of opposition. In 1 Corinthians, Paul describes his own weakness and fear, while in Acts, the believers face turmoil and threats from the city rulers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 3, 44, 18, 6, 6, 'in weakness, and in fear, and in much trembling', 'Paul''s Fear and Opposition', 'This connection highlights Paul''s experience of weakness and fear in the face of opposition. Both passages emphasize the challenges he faced while preaching, culminating in his decision to turn to the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 3, 48, 4, 13, 14, 'in weakness, and in fear, and in much trembling', 'Connection of Weakness and Infirmity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of weakness and infirmity in the context of preaching the gospel. In 1 Corinthians, Paul speaks of his own weakness, while in Galatians, he refers to his infirmity of the flesh during his initial preaching.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 4, 46, 4, 20, 20, 'in demonstration of the Spirit and of power', 'Power in God''s Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of power over mere words. The demonstration of the Spirit and of power in preaching aligns with the assertion that the kingdom of God is characterized by power rather than just words.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 4, 52, 1, 5, 5, 'in demonstration of the Spirit and of power', 'Connection of Power and Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of power and the Holy Spirit in the preaching of the gospel. This connection highlights the importance of divine influence in the effectiveness of the message shared by the apostles.', 'theme', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 4, 46, 1, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Preaching and Wisdom', 'Both passages emphasize the avoidance of human wisdom in preaching. They highlight the importance of demonstrating the Spirit and power over eloquent speech, ensuring the message of the cross remains effective.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 4, 45, 15, 19, 19, 'demonstration of the Spirit and of power', 'Power of the Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Spirit and power in preaching the gospel. They highlight that true effectiveness in ministry comes not from human wisdom but through divine demonstration.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(46, 2, 4, 61, 1, 16, 16, 'demonstration of the Spirit and of power', 'Connection of Power and Witness', 'Both passages emphasize the demonstration of power in relation to the truth of the Gospel. 1 Corinthians highlights the Spirit''s power in preaching, while 2 Peter asserts the eyewitness testimony of Christ''s majesty as a demonstration of that power.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
